# agent-os build configuration.
#
# Seeded from bazel-experiments/compile-zig-wasm — the validated Zig-0.16-on-Bazel
# setup the VISION (§7.1) tells us to reuse. Each line is load-bearing; the comment
# says WHY so the next reader can extend without re-deriving it (C1).

# Bzlmod only — no legacy WORKSPACE. The whole graph is declared in MODULE.bazel.
common --enable_workspace=false

# Tests and tools locate inputs via runfiles, never hardcoded paths. This is what
# kills the memcontainers `../../target/...` staleness class at the source (§2.2).
common --enable_runfiles

# Hermetic actions: the action environment is the declared one, not the caller's
# shell. No tool leaks in from $PATH (B4).
common --incompatible_strict_action_env

# Third-party C/C++ (sqlite, luau) is compiled by the hermetic `zig cc`; silence
# upstream warnings so they don't drown our own diagnostics.
common --copt=-w
common --host_copt=-w

# No global target platform: host-side tools (the contracts projector, later the
# server) build for the autodetected host. musl is a property of the ONE binary that
# links a prebuilt libwasmtime.a — hosts/wasmtime — and is applied there per-target in
# Step 2 (//platforms:host_musl), not forced on the whole repo (VISION §8.1). Kernel
# and guest targets transition to //platforms:wasm32_freestanding via the Zig wasm
# toolchain regardless of this default.

# Zig 0.16's `zig translate-c` (used by @cImport) resolves its cache from the
# environment; rules_zig points ZIG_GLOBAL_CACHE_DIR under /tmp. Mount the real
# /tmp into the sandbox so that cache is writable and shared across actions.
build --sandbox_add_mount_pair=/tmp

# Show what actually failed, not a wall of passing output.
test --test_output=errors

# --- Elixir control-plane lane (//server/otp_hello) — see //MODULE.bazel ----------------
# Registries are GLOBAL because Bzlmod module resolution is global. The rabbitmq
# erlang-packages registry is only consulted for modules absent from the BCR (the erlang hex
# deps), and the BCR stays FIRST, so existing resolutions are unchanged. Specifying any
# --registry replaces the default list, so the BCR must be named explicitly.
common --registry=https://bcr.bazel.build/
common --registry=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rabbitmq/bazel-central-registry/erlang-packages/

# Toolchain SELECTION is scoped to `--config=elixir`, NEVER global: a global erlang
# --host_platform/--platforms would clobber the wasm/Rust/Zig builds (which is the whole point
# of the "No global target platform" note above). The dual-platform dance rules_erlang needs:
# the HOST platform carries *_internal (→ build OTP+Elixir from source), the TARGET platform
# carries the version constraints (→ select the toolchains). The //server/otp_hello targets
# are target_compatible_with erlang_26_2, so plain `bazel build //...` skips them and only
# `--config=elixir` builds them. Usage: bazel test //server/otp_hello:mix_test --config=elixir
build:elixir --host_platform=//platforms:erlang_internal_platform
build:elixir --platforms=//platforms:erlang_linux_26_2_platform
